title: Parametric Build Plate Support for Delta Printer

description.text:
I needed some sort of support for the build plate on the Delta printer I am designing & came up with this idea.  There are quite a few variables you can change, but most of the ones you really need to adjust to your design are nearest to the top of the program.  I still have not decided on the size my Delta will be which is another reason I wanted to be able to easily change the sizes.  I included STL files for 3 sizes.  The 310mm OD & 220mm OD are probably the most common used.  This design may change, since I am not sure whether the heat bed & glass will attach directly to this or whether I need to make another bracket for that.  The large 406mm OD I had to make in six 60 degree wings to fit on my print bed.  I might have been able to make it in three 120 degree wings if I made the center Internal diameter larger.  You have a choice of 30, 60, 90, or 120 degree wings although 90 probably does not work well for a delta.  Let me know if any of the variables do not work as expected.  It is difficult to check every possibility.
I included openscad files for the wing & brackets.  Make sure you make the  bracket hole sizes & offsets the same on main file as well as the brackets you use.  I used M3 bolts & 12mm long & locknuts will work in the current configuration.  I only M3x14mm & M3x16mm, so they will work but the bolt will extend beyond the locknut.  The default hole size is 3.5mm which works for M3 bolts on my machine.  I originally used M4 bolts, but it did not seem like they were really needed.  For the center supports, you can use either a circular or the smaller oval brackets.  I would test print 1 or 2 wings with the brackets before printing all the parts.  For your situation, the STL files I included may not work for you, but you can easily change them with the customizer or using openscad or your machine.  I thought with the larger size I am starting with, the circular bracket would give better support.  This Part will have some flex in it, but with a delta just about all the weight should only be at the 3 points along the outside of this build plate support.  I think 120 degree wings are the ideal size to use.   You might be able to make a square version with this, but you will probably have to adjust the code some.
One of the photos I show it connected at the top of my delta as it was easier to photograph.  I am using 3/4" electrical conduit (EMT) for the horizontal supports in my design.
I printed my parts at 40% infill .2mm layer height.  The customizer version (ParametricBuildPlateWings_rev22.scad) defaults to the settings I used for the 310mm OD & 300mm Hole Pattern.  There are lots of possibilities, so play with the variables until you get to the design that works best for you.

remixed_from.title: Wanhao duplicator i3 <=V1 - Glass bed XY corner clamp

description.text:
I wanted a simple corner for my Wanhao/Monoprice i3 bed. I intend on using several glass beds and wanted a design I could use to drop these glass beds in at will.
This is a remix, however I have made several modifications. Starting at the bottom, I rounded the base of the object so that it takes up less space on the heating mat. Next the center mount hole was moved closer to the corner and elongated. This will allow the corner clamp to butt up directly to the corner of the bed. The elongated hole and the recessed arc of the corner should allow the user to push the corner into the bed and crank down the nut. It's recommended to use a washer and thread lock nut directly under this piece. The stock spring fits over them just fine.
The piece also does not have adjustable bolts. I have extended the piece and it's intended for a piece of glass cut exactly to the size of the bed with small corners nipped out to make room for the bed bolts. Any glass cutters will do this for you if you're unable to do it yourself. Though with a little practice glass cutting is fun and easy!

I like some of the vases I've found here but being a tinkerer, I wanted to make changes.  I quickly found myself dealing with math that I haven't touched in over 20 years.  It was a great learning experience and open ended with possibilities.  This first post will be some of my early designs.  I will post others later once I'm happy with them.
I've printed these in ABS, HIPS and PLA.  I'd recommend a 1mm shell at 0.25mm resolution.  These are hollow objects so you don't have to mess with infill or removing the top layer.
I'm including the OpenSCAD files so others like me can play with the designs.  Note that the basic vase prints just fine at a lower granularity (higher numbers).  You will see the vertical and horizontal parameters (vgrain and hgrain) at the top of the file.  The more complex vases need to set vgrain and hgrain to 1.  Be aware that they take forever to render.  The designs do seem to scale well.  The straight fluted vase in the picture was scales to 2 before printing.
I've commented the OpenSCAD files but here are some generalities.  Each vase is drawn by layers.  Each layer is broken into wedges.  The size is controlled by vgrain and hgrain.  There is a mathimatical formula to represent the layer.  For the basic vases it is just the trig formula for a circle.  Additionally there is a mathimatical formula that represents the vertical profile of the vase.  In the basic vase file I've included four profiles.  All of them are based on the cosine function and its harmonics.  I've included a file called vase_profile.scad which allows you to quickly see what a profile might look like.  It is how I came up with the profiles I'm using.
Be aware that if you change the formula for generating fluting or make the diameter too small you may run into errors.  What happens is the nice arc shapes actually generate loops that loop back on themselves.  For example the stuff you might see from playing with a Spirograph as a kid.  The loop backs cause the left points of the wedge to be less than the right points of the wedge and create an invalid shape.  They seem to work in the quick preview but when you render, they will throw errors.  Enjoy.

Important Note - Design problem: (1-1-2016) the tabs where the screw goes through severed in a crash three days ago. I have reworked the top and will print and fly the new version this week. When I get a leg that doesn't crack at the screw hole tab, I will upload it. You could try printing the posted version at a much higher fill than the 40% I used on the original and increase the Z scale. However, I really think it is going to need the top reworked. More soon... This is my design for new landing legs for Armattan's 330 quadcopter- FPV Rev2. I printed them with Taulman 618 nylon filament. So I am not the greatest pilot and I was always breaking off the standoff style landing pegs that came with the quad. I've been flying and landing pretty hard on occasion with these and they are holding up well. You can increase the Z-axis on the print if you want to make them stiffer. You will want to use nylon. I tried semi flex, PLA, ABS. Semi is too soft, PLA is too brittle, nylon is just right. The nylon provides a nice cushion for landing, too
The legs lock on the arm and I secure them in place with the screw that came with the kit using a washed and lock nut (see photo). You will need to mark and drill that one hole - 3mm.

LoboCNC, your design for the Frankenstein Light Switch was great.  Only problem was the 2 up modern was too wide for my Printrbot Simple with a limit of Y 100m.  I'm sure there are people out there with the same limitation.  You'll need an extended X axis, which is easy enough to do.  But this print will print easily in Y 100mm.  
The trick was that I could cut Lobo's Modern 2 Up in half.  It figured it had to be symmetrical so this worked.  Kudos Lobo, I love the switch.
Problem with my computer room is that one switch turns on the lights.  The other turns power on to certain sockets.  I'd also hit the wrong one and shut down half the lab.  Splitting the print into 2 simplified my lab.  White Lights, Black Power.

title: Arm Bumper for Armattan F1-5 and F1-6

description.text:
Some durable bumpers that are pretty quick to print. They just slip on to the end of the arm, providing the edge of your valuable carbon fiber with some decent protection from inevitable future encounters with pavement...
The idea is that they are cheap and fast to print at around 15 mins each, so print a few extra in case you lose one. Typically in a crash, they'll take the initial impact and remain on the frame. In cartwheeling crashes they'll probably pop off. I haven't actually broken or lost one yet.

No

Yes

0.2mm

100%

Notes: I've printed them in PLA, but I'm certain that ABS would work just as well. You cold even try some flexy stuff like FliaFlex, NinjaFlex, or generic TPE. Print with supports or without; I've done both. title: FatShark 600TVL FPV Camera Tilt Mount for Armattan F1

description.text:
A tilt mount for your Fatshark 600TVL fpv cam. I've designed it specifically with the Armattan F1 in mind, but it's a fairly common method of mounting an FPV cam these days so it should work on a handful of other quads as well. 
The camera is simply popped in from the back of the mount. The lens cover will not fit through the opening, so you'll have to remove it to install the mount. If you printed it face down the ridges from the print layers should grab the seam between the 2 halves of the camera and hold it in place quite well. If it loosens off over time and no longer stays put, just put a dab of hot glue on the edge. 
The tilt holds OK with friction alone, but you should really use a dab of hot glue on each pivot to fix it in place at your desired tilt angle.

description.text: Introducing the core set for our (years in the making) tabletop miniature wargame system, Wayfarer Tactics! Based on the vastly open Multiverse setting from our tabletop RPG, Wayfarer: Things Beyond Wonder, Wayfarer Tactics gives you a comprehensive tool set to adapt miniatures from any genre (fantasy, science fiction, modern, et cetera) at any scale and play fast, decisive battles with resolution based on our Pocket-Tactics core dice mechanics. Wayfarer Tactics was recently successfully Kickstarted and, as promised, we've released the rules codex free and open sourced. You can download it here with the models or on our website. If you or someone you know is into tabletop miniature gaming, come check it out! This set was designed for 18mm scale gaming, and includes special rulers (with 2-cm increments), though you can feel free to use inches or centimeters if you prefer. The factions included would also be easy enough to proxy with lots of 28mm miniatures that are available out there. For this core set, you'll need 6 red dice, 6 blue dice, a couple of white dice, two decks of playing cards, and you'll want to print: Sorceress x1, Hobgoblin Brute x4, Hobgoblin Archer x3, Goblin Wretch x7, Goblin Warlock x1, Freespace Merc Captain x1, Freespace Merc Technician x1, Freespace Merc Heavy Support x1, Freespace Merc Trooper x3, Spotter Drone x2, Trooper Casualty x1, Measuring Stick x2, Ruined Wall A x1, Ruined Wall B x1, Ruined Wall C x1, Ruined Wall D x1, Ruined Wall E x1, Well x1, Rubble Pile A x2, Rubble Pile B x2, and Ruined Wall Corner and Corner Upper Floor x4 each. We've set up a Patreon page for anyone who's interested to help fund us so we can keep making free and open sourced games like Pocket-Tactics, Wayfarer Tactics. and others, not to mention the growing catalog of gaming miniatures that you can use for whatever you want! (Psst... we take requests and commissions...) Enjoy!

description.text: Four two part ornaments.  Each part holds a pattern and the parts can be rotated with respect to each other.  Classic  moire patterns are formed when two identical patterns are overlaid and slightly offset.  These ornaments exhibit that behavior.  In addition two unrelated types can be rotated against each other making many curious patterns.  A simple openSCAD program which illustrates the rotation of the ornaments is included.

0.2 mm

Notes: These large flat objects can be printed directly on the build platform. However printing with a raft reduces their tendency to curl at the edge. Makerbot software allows the distance from the raft to the printed object to be increased to aid in the removal of the raft.

How to Use the Ornaments The ornaments can be adjusted to show an interesting pattern and used as window decorations - see the included picture. When viewed over a piece of white paper and quickly rotated back and forth the somewhat surreal creation of a moire fringe is observed. To make the ornaments easy to rotate it may be necessary to use sand paper and a bit of lubricant. The bumps at the outer edge of the inner parts are meant to make rotation easier.
